{"title_page": "Eurotech Racing", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Motor racing team\n| name           = {{flagicon|GBR}} Eurotech Racing\n|logo             = \n| founded        = 1987\n| principal      = [[Jeff Smith (racing driver)|Jeff Smith]]<br />[[Marvin Humphries]]\n| current series = [[British Touring Car Championship|BTCC]]\n| former series  = [[British GT Championship|British GT]]\n| drivers        = [[Martin Depper]]<br>[[Jeff Smith (racing driver)|Jeff Smith]]\n| driver titles  = [[2012 British Touring Car Championship season|2012]] [[British Touring Car Championship|{{H:title|Independent BTCC|Ind. BTCC}}]] <small>([[Andrew Jordan (racing driver)|Jordan]])</small><br>[[2013 British Touring Car Championship season|2013]] [[British Touring Car Championship|BTCC]] <small>([[Andrew Jordan (racing driver)|Jordan]])</small><br>[[2013 British Touring Car Championship season|2013]] [[British Touring Car Championship|{{H:title|Independent BTCC|Ind. BTCC}}]] <small>([[Andrew Jordan (racing driver)|Jordan]])</small>\n| team titles    = [[2012 British Touring Car Championship season|2012]] [[British Touring Car Championship|{{H:title|Independent BTCC|Ind. BTCC}}]]<br>[[2013 British Touring Car Championship season|2013]] [[British Touring Car Championship|{{H:title|Independent BTCC|Ind. BTCC}}]]\n| Website        = http://www.eurotechracing.co.uk/\n}}\n\n'''Eurotech Racing''' is a [[United Kingdom|British]] motor racing team based in [[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]], [[Staffordshire]], founded by [[Mike Jordan (racing driver)|Mike Jordan]] and currently owned by [[Jeff Smith (racing driver)|Jeff Smith]] since December 2014.\n\nThe team won both the BTCC independent teams trophy and the independent drivers' championship with [[Andrew Jordan (racing driver)|Andrew Jordan]] in 2012.\n\n==British Touring Car Championship==\n\n===Honda Integra (2006\u20132008)===\nTeam Eurotech entered the BTCC in [[2006 British Touring Car Championship season|2006]] with Mike Jordan driving a [[Honda Integra]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Meissner|first=Johan|title=BTCC 2006 entry list released|url=http://www.touringcartimes.com/article.php?id=271|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120913235400/http://www.touringcartimes.com/article.php?id=271|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 September 2012|work=TouringCarTimes|publisher=Mediaempire Stockholm AB|accessdate=22 February 2013|date=29 March 2006}}</ref> He made history by becoming the oldest BTCC race winner in 2006 at the age of 48 when he won the third race of the day at [[Mondello Park]]. The penultimate race of the season at [[Silverstone Circuit|Silverstone]] saw Jordan crash with [[SEAT Sport|SEAT Sport UK]] drivers [[Jason Plato]] and [[James Thompson (racing driver)|James Thompson]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Titles for Neal, SEAT & Team Halfords at Silverstone|url=http://www.btcc.net/html/generalnews_detail.php?id=348&month=10&year=2006&form=browse&searchterm=|work=[[British Touring Car Championship]]|publisher=[[TOCA]]|accessdate=23 February 2013|date=15 October 2006}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He was then airlifted to the [[University Hospital Coventry]] with severe head injuries and a punctured lung.<ref>{{cite news|last=Veltman|first=Rob|title=BTCC Statement: Mike Jordan|url=http://www.touringcartimes.com/article.php?id=750|work=TouringCarTimes|publisher=Mediaempire Stockholm AB|accessdate=23 February 2013|date=15 October 2006}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Jordan finished the season tenth in the drivers' championship with two podiums an addition to his win while the team was fifth in the teams championship.\n\nMike Jordan recovered over the winter and he returned as the team's driver for [[2007 British Touring Car Championship season|2007]]. With the championship moving to [[Super 2000]] technical regulations, the Honda Integra would no longer be eligible for the overall drivers' championship.<ref>{{cite news|last=Freeman|first=Glenn|title=Jordan not surprised by testing pace|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/57305|work=[[Autosport]]|publisher=[[Haymarket Media Group|Haymarket Publications]]|accessdate=23 February 2013|date=14 March 2007}}</ref> The team took four podium finishes on the way to sixth in the teams' championship, one position down on the best placed single car entry of [[Mat Jackson|Jackson Msport]].\n\nFor [[2008 British Touring Car Championship season|2008]] the team expanded to two cars to run Mike Jordan and his son Andrew in a pair of Honda Integras.<ref>{{cite news|last=Veltman|first=Rob|title=Andrew Jordan begins BTCC career|url=http://www.touringcartimes.com/article.php?id=1548|work=TouringCarTimes|publisher=Mediaempire Stockholm AB|accessdate=23 February 2013|date=20 October 2007}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Andrew got his first podium result in the third race at [[Oulton Park]] by finishing third, he did the same at the next round at [[Knockhill Racing Circuit|Knockhill]] three weeks later. He finished one place ahead of his father in the championship in thirteenth place while the team ended the season eighth in the teams' championship.\n\nEurotech purchased a S2000 [[Vauxhall Vectra]] for the [[2009 British Touring Car Championship season|2009 season]] with support from [[Triple 8 Race Engineering]]. Andrew Jordan was to drive the car with Mike Jordan retiring from driving in the championship.<ref>{{cite news|last=Meissner|first=Johan|title=Jordan to drive Vauxhall Vectra in 2009|url=http://www.touringcartimes.com/article.php?id=2749|work=TouringCarTimes|publisher=Mediaempire Stockholm AB|accessdate=23 February 2013|date=30 September 2008}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> This later changed when Andrew joined the factory VX Racing team and Eurotech did not enter their own car for 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last=English|first=Steven|title=Jordan joins works Vauxhall squad|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/72656/|work=[[Autosport]]|publisher=[[Haymarket Media Group|Haymarket Publications]]|accessdate=23 February 2013|date=8 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Vauxhall Vectra (2010\u20132011)===\nUnder the Pirtek Racing banner, Eurotech ran a Vauxhall Vectra in the [[2010 British Touring Car Championship season|2010 season]] for Andrew Jordan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Turbo Vectra for Jordan|url=http://www.btcc.net/html/generalnews_detail.php?id=1773&month=0&year=2013&form=search&searchterm=Pirtek|work=[[British Touring Car Championship]]|publisher=[[TOCA]]|accessdate=22 February 2013|date=2 December 2009}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The car was powered by the new [[Next Generation Touring Car|NGTC]] turbocharged engine which ran well in preseason testing.<ref>{{cite news|title=Strong first run for NGTC engine|url=http://www.btcc.net/html/generalnews_detail.php?id=1826|work=[[British Touring Car Championship]]|publisher=[[TOCA]]|accessdate=1 March 2010|date=26 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219162918/http://www.btcc.net/html/generalnews_detail.php?id=1826|archive-date=19 February 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Andrew Jordan took the first win for both himself and the [[TOCA]] NGTC engine at [[Croft Circuit]], leading every lap from pole position to beat [[Arena Motorsport|Team Aon]]'s [[Tom Onslow-Cole]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Jordan, NGTC engine's first win|url=http://www.btcc.net/html/generalnews_detail.php?id=2007|work=[[British Touring Car Championship]]|publisher=[[TOCA]]|accessdate=22 February 2013|date=20 June 2010}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He then took his second victory in the season finale at [[Brands Hatch|Brands Hatch Indy]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Hodges|first=Peter|title=Andrew Jordan wins final race of the year|url=http://www.touringcartimes.com/article.php?id=5400|work=TouringCarTimes|publisher=Mediaempire Stockholm AB|accessdate=22 February 2013|date=10 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101015134404/http://www.touringcartimes.com/article.php?id=5400|archive-date=15 October 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> At the end of the season, the team were the teams championship and sixth in the sixth in the independent teams trophy.\n\nIn [[2011 British Touring Car Championship season|2011]], it was announced that Pirtek Racing would enter two cars for Andrew Jordan and former [[Renault Clio Cup United Kingdom]] driver, [[Jeff Smith (racing driver)|Jeff Smith]].<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Leary|first=Jamie|title=Smith joins Eurotech for 2011|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/88553|work=[[Autosport]]|publisher=[[Haymarket Media Group|Haymarket Publications]]|accessdate=22 February 2013|date=2 December 2010}}</ref> Jordan took the team's only win of the season at [[Donington Park]].\n\n===Honda Civic (2012\u20132018)===\nFor [[2012 British Touring Car Championship season|2012]], the team switched to a pair of NGTC specification [[Honda Civic]]s that were identical to the cars used by the works [[Team Dynamics|Honda Racing]] squad, while retaining the same lineup from the previous season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pirtek also going NGTC|url=http://www.btcc.net/html/generalnews_detail.php?id=2655|work=[[British Touring Car Championship]]|publisher=[[TOCA]]|accessdate=22 February 2013|date=21 September 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401102613/http://www.btcc.net/html/generalnews_detail.php?id=2655|archivedate=1 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Andrew Jordan claimed the team's first pole position at [[Thruxton Circuit|Thruxton]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Jordan grabs Thruxton pole|url=http://www.btcc.net/html/generalnews_detail.php?id=2955|work=[[British Touring Car Championship]]|publisher=[[TOCA]]|accessdate=22 February 2013|date=28 April 2012}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Similarly to the previous season, the team took only one win from the thirty races, with Andrew Jordan taking the checkered flag in race two at Snetterton. However, Smith scored a breakthrough result of second place at [[Knockhill]] in the third race, after a race-long battle with defending champion [[Matt Neal]]. Andrew Jordan finished the season fourth overall and entered the final round at Brands Hatch with a mathematical chance of securing the overall Drivers' Championship. He did however win the HiQ Independents' Trophy as the highest scoring independent driver.\nThe team ended the season third overall in the Teams' Championship and also secured the Independent Teams' Championship after a season long battle with [[Motorbase Performance|Redstone Racing]] and [[West Surrey Racing|eBay Motors]].\n\nThe team stayed in the BTCC in [[2013 British Touring Car Championship season|2013]] with Andrew Jordan to defend their independent titles.<ref>{{cite news|last=Turner|first=Kevin|title=Andrew Jordan targets overall BTCC title in 2013|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/103674|work=[[Autosport]]|publisher=[[Haymarket Media Group|Haymarket Publications]]|accessdate=22 February 2013|date=25 October 2012}}</ref> The team later confirmed that Smith would also remain at the team alongside Jordan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jeff Smith continues with Eurotech in 2013 BTCC|url=http://www.touringcartimes.com/article.php?id=8595|work=TouringCarTimes|publisher=Mediaempire Stockholm AB|accessdate=22 February 2013|date=19 February 2013}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> It proved to be the team's most successful year, as Jordan won the overall championship.  After an unsuccessful defence of the title in [[2014 British Touring Car Championship season|2014]], Jordan left the team for [[Triple Eight Racing]] and his father sold Eurotech to Smith, who is now the team's owner-driver for [[2015 British Touring Car Championship season|2015]] alongside [[Martin Depper]]. Once again this year was disappointing for the team with [[Jeff Smith (racing driver)|Jeff Smith]] Finishing in 20th in the standings with 31 points and [[Martin Depper]] finishing 18th in the standings with 51 points.<ref>https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/british-touring-car-championship/2015/</ref>\n\nIn the [[2016 British Touring Car Championship]] the team fielded the same lineup as [[2015 British Touring Car Championship season|2015]] while also adding [[Daniel Lloyd (racing driver)|Daniel Lloyd]] for race weekends 3\u20135. Lloyd achieved 3 jack sears trophy wins (Round 8 at [[Thruxton Circuit]] and rounds 10 and 11 at [[Oulton Park]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Jack Sears Trophy honours for Lloyd| url=http://www.btcc.net/2016/05/11/jack-sears-trophy-honours-for-lloyd/|work=BTCC.net}}</ref> For 2016, [[Jeff Smith (racing driver)|Jeff Smith]] Finished top of the Eurotech Drivers in 18th place with 55 points, [[Daniel Lloyd (racing driver)|Lloyd]]  finished in 20th place with 36 points and [[Martin Depper]] finished in 21st place with 28 points.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dunlop MSA British Touring Car Championship 2016 standings| url=https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/british-touring-car-championship/2016/|work=driverdb.com}}</ref> Overall the team finished in 13th in the teams championship with 105 points.\n\nFor [[2017 British Touring Car Championship|2017]] the team returned with [[Jeff Smith (racing driver)|Jeff Smith]] and added [[Jack Goff]] from [[West Surrey Racing|Team IHG rewards club]]. Smith However suffered a crash during a wet qualifying session at [[Croft Circuit]]<ref>{{cite news|title= Horror BTCC crash leaves trio in hospital| url=https://www.racefans.net/2017/06/12/three-drivers-hospitalised-in-btcc-weekend/| work=Racefans.net}}</ref> and was replaced by his son, [[Brett Smith (racing driver)|Brett]] from round 16 at [[Snetterton Circuit|Snetterton]] onwards. [[Brett Smith (racing driver)|Brett]] would go on to win two Jack sears trophy wins in rounds 26 at [[Silverstone Circuit]] and round 29 at [[Brands Hatch|Brands Hatch Indy]]. While [[Jack Goff]] won the race for round 26 and was the winning independent driver on 4 occasions, on his way to 6th in the championship(245 points), the teams best performance since [[2014 British Touring Car Championship season|2014]] when [[Andrew Jordan (racing driver)|Andrew Jordan]] finished 5th. Brett smith would go on to finish 30th on 13 points with Jeff smith 26th with 25 points. The team finished in 5th place with 286 points.\n\nFor [[2018 British Touring Car Championship|2018]] the team rebranded to Wix racing with Eurotech.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wix Filters unveiled as new Eurotech Title sponsor| url=http://www.btcc.net/2018/02/20/wix-filters-unveiled-as-eurotech-racing-title-sponsors/|work=BTCC.net}}</ref> Sticking with the same driver lineup as the end of  [[2017 British Touring Car Championship|2017]], the team still saw some success with 2 pole positions for Jack Goff and 1 for Brett smith, with Goff also grabbing 2 wins as well. [[Jack Goff|Goff]] would take 8th place in the drivers championship with 228 points with  [[Brett Smith (racing driver)|Smith]] taking 20th on 70 points.The team would finish 6th in the Teams Championship and 3rd in the Independents Championship.\n\nAfter 2018 the team Withdrew from the champioship marking the end of their 12-year run in the [[British Touring Car Championship]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Eurotech Racing sells BTCC Licence, will not compete in 2019| url=https://www.autosport.com/btcc/news/139105/eurotech-racing-team-withdraws-from-btcc|work=Autosport|publisher=Motorsports Network}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.eurotechracing.co.uk/}}\n* [http://www.pirtek.co.uk/pirtek-racing.aspx#.USfjZSrKfD9  Pirtek Racing]\n\n{{BTCC teams}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eurotech Racing}}\n[[Category:British auto racing teams]]\n[[Category:Auto racing teams established in 1987]]\n[[Category:1987 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:British Touring Car Championship teams]]\n[[Category:Porsche Supercup teams]]\n[[Category:British GT Championship teams]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Motor racing team\n| name           = {{flagicon|GBR}} Eurotech Racing\n|logo             = \n| founded        = 1987\n| principal      = [[Jeff Smith (racing driver)|Jeff Smith]]<br />[[Marvin Humphries]]\n| current series = [[British Touring Car Championship|BTCC]]\n| former series  = [[British GT Championship|British GT]]\n| drivers        = [[Martin Depper]]<br>[[Jeff Smith (racing driver)|Jeff Smith]]\n| driver titles  = [[2012 British Touring Car Championship season|2012]] [[British Touring Car Championship|{{H:title|Independent BTCC|Ind. BTCC}}]] <small>([[Andrew Jordan (racing driver)|Jordan]])</small><br>[[2013 British Touring Car Championship season|2013]] [[British Touring Car Championship|BTCC]] <small>([[Andrew Jordan (racing driver)|Jordan]])</small><br>[[2013 British Touring Car Championship season|2013]] [[British Touring Car Championship|{{H:title|Independent BTCC|Ind. BTCC}}]] <small>([[Andrew Jordan (racing driver)|Jordan]])</small>\n| team titles    = [[2012 British Touring Car Championship season|2012]] [[British Touring Car Championship|{{H:title|Independent BTCC|Ind. BTCC}}]]<br>[[2013 British Touring Car Championship season|2013]] [[British Touring Car Championship|{{H:title|Independent BTCC|Ind. BTCC}}]]\n| Website        = http://www.eurotechracing.co.uk/\n}}\n\n'''Eurotech Racing''' is a [[United Kingdom|British]] motor racing team based in [[Tamworth, Staffordshire|Tamworth]], [[Staffordshire]], founded by [[Mike Jordan (racing driver)|Mike Jordan]] and currently owned by [[Jeff Smith (racing driver)|Jeff Smith]] since December 2014.\n\nThe team won both the BTCC independent teams trophy and the independent drivers' championship with [[Andrew Jordan (racing driver)|Andrew Jordan]] in 2012.\n\n==British Touring Car Championship==\n\n===Honda Integra (2006\u20132008)===\nTeam Eurotech entered the BTCC in [[2006 British Touring Car Championship season|2006]] with Mike Jordan driving a [[Honda Integra]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Meissner|first=Johan|title=BTCC 2006 entry list released|url=http://www.touringcartimes.com/article.php?id=271|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120913235400/http://www.touringcartimes.com/article.php?id=271|url-status=dead|archive-date=13 September 2012|work=TouringCarTimes|publisher=Mediaempire Stockholm AB|accessdate=22 February 2013|date=29 March 2006}}</ref> He made history by becoming the oldest BTCC race winner in 2006 at the age of 48 when he won the third race of the day at [[Mondello Park]]. The penultimate race of the season at [[Silverstone Circuit|Silverstone]] saw Jordan crash with [[SEAT Sport|SEAT Sport UK]] drivers [[Jason Plato]] and [[James Thompson (racing driver)|James Thompson]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Titles for Neal, SEAT & Team Halfords at Silverstone|url=http://www.btcc.net/html/generalnews_detail.php?id=348&month=10&year=2006&form=browse&searchterm=|work=[[British Touring Car Championship]]|publisher=[[TOCA]]|accessdate=23 February 2013|date=15 October 2006}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He was then airlifted to the [[University Hospital Coventry]] with severe head injuries and a punctured lung.<ref>{{cite news|last=Veltman|first=Rob|title=BTCC Statement: Mike Jordan|url=http://www.touringcartimes.com/article.php?id=750|work=TouringCarTimes|publisher=Mediaempire Stockholm AB|accessdate=23 February 2013|date=15 October 2006}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Jordan finished the season tenth in the drivers' championship with two podiums an addition to his win while the team was fifth in the teams championship.\n\nMike Jordan recovered over the winter and he returned as the team's driver for [[2007 British Touring Car Championship season|2007]]. With the championship moving to [[Super 2000]] technical regulations, the Honda Integra would no longer be eligible for the overall drivers' championship.<ref>{{cite news|last=Freeman|first=Glenn|title=Jordan not surprised by testing pace|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/57305|work=[[Autosport]]|publisher=[[Haymarket Media Group|Haymarket Publications]]|accessdate=23 February 2013|date=14 March 2007}}</ref> The team took four podium finishes on the way to sixth in the teams' championship, one position down on the best placed single car entry of [[Mat Jackson|Jackson Msport]].\n\nFor [[2008 British Touring Car Championship season|2008]] the team expanded to two cars to run Mike Jordan and his son Andrew in a pair of Honda Integras.<ref>{{cite news|last=Veltman|first=Rob|title=Andrew Jordan begins BTCC career|url=http://www.touringcartimes.com/article.php?id=1548|work=TouringCarTimes|publisher=Mediaempire Stockholm AB|accessdate=23 February 2013|date=20 October 2007}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Andrew got his first podium result in the third race at [[Oulton Park]] by finishing third, he did the same at the next round at [[Knockhill Racing Circuit|Knockhill]] three weeks later. He finished one place ahead of his father in the championship in thirteenth place while the team ended the season eighth in the teams' championship.\n\nEurotech purchased a S2000 [[Vauxhall Vectra]] for the [[2009 British Touring Car Championship season|2009 season]] with support from [[Triple 8 Race Engineering]]. Andrew Jordan was to drive the car with Mike Jordan retiring from driving in the championship.<ref>{{cite news|last=Meissner|first=Johan|title=Jordan to drive Vauxhall Vectra in 2009|url=http://www.touringcartimes.com/article.php?id=2749|work=TouringCarTimes|publisher=Mediaempire Stockholm AB|accessdate=23 February 2013|date=30 September 2008}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> This later changed when Andrew joined the factory VX Racing team and Eurotech did not enter their own car for 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last=English|first=Steven|title=Jordan joins works Vauxhall squad|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/72656/|work=[[Autosport]]|publisher=[[Haymarket Media Group|Haymarket Publications]]|accessdate=23 February 2013|date=8 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Vauxhall Vectra (2010\u20132011)===\nUnder the Pirtek Racing banner, Eurotech ran a Vauxhall Vectra in the [[2010 British Touring Car Championship season|2010 season]] for Andrew Jordan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Turbo Vectra for Jordan|url=http://www.btcc.net/html/generalnews_detail.php?id=1773&month=0&year=2013&form=search&searchterm=Pirtek|work=[[British Touring Car Championship]]|publisher=[[TOCA]]|accessdate=22 February 2013|date=2 December 2009}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The car was powered by the new [[Next Generation Touring Car|NGTC]] turbocharged engine which ran well in preseason testing.<ref>{{cite news|title=Strong first run for NGTC engine|url=http://www.btcc.net/html/generalnews_detail.php?id=1826|work=[[British Touring Car Championship]]|publisher=[[TOCA]]|accessdate=1 March 2010|date=26 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219162918/http://www.btcc.net/html/generalnews_detail.php?id=1826|archive-date=19 February 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Andrew Jordan took the first win for both himself and the [[TOCA]] NGTC engine at [[Croft Circuit]], leading every lap from pole position to beat [[Arena Motorsport|Team Aon]]'s [[Tom Onslow-Cole]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Jordan, NGTC engine's first win|url=http://www.btcc.net/html/generalnews_detail.php?id=2007|work=[[British Touring Car Championship]]|publisher=[[TOCA]]|accessdate=22 February 2013|date=20 June 2010}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He then took his second victory in the season finale at [[Brands Hatch|Brands Hatch Indy]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Hodges|first=Peter|title=Andrew Jordan wins final race of the year|url=http://www.touringcartimes.com/article.php?id=5400|work=TouringCarTimes|publisher=Mediaempire Stockholm AB|accessdate=22 February 2013|date=10 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101015134404/http://www.touringcartimes.com/article.php?id=5400|archive-date=15 October 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> At the end of the season, the team were the teams championship and sixth in the sixth in the independent teams trophy.\n\nIn [[2011 British Touring Car Championship season|2011]], it was announced that Pirtek Racing would enter two cars for Andrew Jordan and former [[Renault Clio Cup United Kingdom]] driver, [[Jeff Smith (racing driver)|Jeff Smith]].<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Leary|first=Jamie|title=Smith joins Eurotech for 2011|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/88553|work=[[Autosport]]|publisher=[[Haymarket Media Group|Haymarket Publications]]|accessdate=22 February 2013|date=2 December 2010}}</ref> Jordan took the team's only win of the season at [[Donington Park]].\n\n===Honda Civic (2012\u20132018)===\nFor [[2012 British Touring Car Championship season|2012]], the team switched to a pair of NGTC specification [[Honda Civic]]s that were identical to the cars used by the works [[Team Dynamics|Honda Racing]] squad, while retaining the same lineup from the previous season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pirtek also going NGTC|url=http://www.btcc.net/html/generalnews_detail.php?id=2655|work=[[British Touring Car Championship]]|publisher=[[TOCA]]|accessdate=22 February 2013|date=21 September 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401102613/http://www.btcc.net/html/generalnews_detail.php?id=2655|archivedate=1 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Andrew Jordan claimed the team's first pole position at [[Thruxton Circuit|Thruxton]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Jordan grabs Thruxton pole|url=http://www.btcc.net/html/generalnews_detail.php?id=2955|work=[[British Touring Car Championship]]|publisher=[[TOCA]]|accessdate=22 February 2013|date=28 April 2012}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Similarly to the previous season, the team took only one win from the thirty races, with Andrew Jordan taking the checkered flag in race two at Snetterton. However, Smith scored a breakthrough result of second place at [[Knockhill]] in the third race, after a race-long battle with defending champion [[Matt Neal]]. Andrew Jordan finished the season fourth overall and entered the final round at Brands Hatch with a mathematical chance of securing the overall Drivers' Championship. He did however win the HiQ Independents' Trophy as the highest scoring independent driver.\nThe team ended the season third overall in the Teams' Championship and also secured the Independent Teams' Championship after a season long battle with [[Motorbase Performance|Redstone Racing]] and [[West Surrey Racing|eBay Motors]].\n\nThe team stayed in the BTCC in [[2013 British Touring Car Championship season|2013]] with Andrew Jordan to defend their independent titles.<ref>{{cite news|last=Turner|first=Kevin|title=Andrew Jordan targets overall BTCC title in 2013|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/103674|work=[[Autosport]]|publisher=[[Haymarket Media Group|Haymarket Publications]]|accessdate=22 February 2013|date=25 October 2012}}</ref> The team later confirmed that Smith would also remain at the team alongside Jordan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jeff Smith continues with Eurotech in 2013 BTCC|url=http://www.touringcartimes.com/article.php?id=8595|work=TouringCarTimes|publisher=Mediaempire Stockholm AB|accessdate=22 February 2013|date=19 February 2013}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> It proved to be the team's most successful year, as Jordan won the overall championship.  After an unsuccessful defence of the title in [[2014 British Touring Car Championship season|2014]], Jordan left the team for [[Triple Eight Racing]] and his father sold Eurotech to Smith, who is now the team's owner-driver for [[2015 British Touring Car Championship season|2015]] alongside [[Martin Depper]]. Once again this year was dissapointing for the team with [[Jeff Smith (racing driver)|Jeff Smith]] Finishing in 20th in the standings with 31 points and [[Martin Depper]] finishing 18th in the standings with 51 points <ref> https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/british-touring-car-championship/2015/</ref>.\n\nIn the [[2016 British Touring Car Championship]] the team fielded the same lineup as [[2015 British Touring Car Championship season|2015]] while also adding [[Daniel Lloyd (racing driver)| Daniel Lloyd]] for race weekends 3-5. Lloyd achieved 3 jack sears trophy wins (Round 8 at [[Thruxton Circuit]] and rounds 10 and 11 at [[Oulton Park]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Jack Sears Trophy honours for Lloyd| url=http://www.btcc.net/2016/05/11/jack-sears-trophy-honours-for-lloyd/|work=BTCC.net}}</ref>. For 2016, [[Jeff Smith (racing driver)|Jeff Smith]] Finished top of the Eurotech Drivers in 18th place with 55 points, [[Daniel Lloyd (racing driver)|Lloyd]]  finished in 20th place with 36 points and [[Martin Depper]] finished in 21st place with 28 points<ref>{{cite news|title=Dunlop MSA British Touring Car Championship 2016 standings| url=https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/british-touring-car-championship/2016/|work=driverdb.com}}</ref>. Overall the team finished in 13th in the teams championship with 105 points.\n\nFor [[2017 British Touring Car Championship|2017]] the team returned with [[Jeff Smith (racing driver)|Jeff Smith]] and added [[Jack Goff]] from [[West Surrey Racing| Team IHG rewards club]]. Smith However suffered a crash during a wet qualifying session at [[Croft Circuit]]<ref>{{cite news|title= Horror BTCC crash leaves trio in hospital| url=https://www.racefans.net/2017/06/12/three-drivers-hospitalised-in-btcc-weekend/| work=Racefans.net}}</ref> and was replaced by his son, [[Brett Smith (racing driver)| Brett]] from round 16 at [[Snetterton Circuit|Snetterton]] onwards. [[Brett Smith (racing driver)| Brett]] would go on to win two Jack sears trophy wins in rounds 26 at [[Silverstone Circuit]] and round 29 at [[Brands Hatch|Brands Hatch Indy]]. While [[Jack Goff]] won the race for round 26 and was the winning independent driver on 4 occasions, on his way to 6th in the championship(245 points), the teams best performance since [[2014 British Touring Car Championship season|2014]] when [[Andrew Jordan (racing driver)| Andrew Jordan]] finished 5th. Brett smith would go on to finish 30th on 13 points with Jeff smith 26th with 25 points. The team finished in 5th place with 286 points.\n\nFor [[2018 British Touring Car Championship|2018]] the team rebranded to Wix racing with Eurotech<ref>{{cite news|title=Wix Filters unveiled as new Eurotech Title sponsor| url=http://www.btcc.net/2018/02/20/wix-filters-unveiled-as-eurotech-racing-title-sponsors/|work=BTCC.net}}</ref>. Sticking with the same driver lineup as the end of  [[2017 British Touring Car Championship|2017]], the team still saw some success with 2 pole positions for Jack Goff and 1 for Brett smith, with Goff also grabbing 2 wins aswell. [[Jack Goff|Goff]] would take 8th place in the drivers championship with 228 points with  [[Brett Smith (racing driver)| Smith]] taking 20th on 70 points.The team would finish 6th in the Teams Championship and 3rd in the Independents Championship.\n\nAfter 2018 the team Withdrew from the champioship marking the end of their 12 year run in the [[British Touring Car Championship]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Eurotech Racing sells BTCC Licence, will not compete in 2019| url=https://www.autosport.com/btcc/news/139105/eurotech-racing-team-withdraws-from-btcc|work=Autosport|publisher=Motorsports Network}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|http://www.eurotechracing.co.uk/}}\n* [http://www.pirtek.co.uk/pirtek-racing.aspx#.USfjZSrKfD9  Pirtek Racing]\n\n{{BTCC teams}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eurotech Racing}}\n[[Category:British auto racing teams]]\n[[Category:Auto racing teams established in 1987]]\n[[Category:1987 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:British Touring Car Championship teams]]\n[[Category:Porsche Supercup teams]]\n[[Category:British GT Championship teams]]\n", "name_user": "Nat965", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHonda Civic (2012\u20132018):ApplyGen fix(es),typo(s) fixed: aswell \u2192 as well, 12 year \u2192 12-year, dissapointing \u2192 disappointing, 3-5 \u2192 3\u20135", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eurotech_Racing"}
